cf6ae58a38252a90f6a82ab4c4e428df.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/1/1d3ac094b2d7bbfcde957e29edd82643f5af8414.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/ac1fcbbde3f168e7c9a4b04e6257bae03b244e40.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/a36cc08cb8dc02e6e284f095c1f95743972262f3.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/b/b926981a641fad976e34946edee0af2e88975cbb.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/6/69ea4fb360541ea40af2742c758877e23debcca3.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/6/6bb0bbdece043dc2c316430250ca47d8daa634f2.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/3/3f5d4f08762604fa3c3745d482e8c9807e7421c2.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/1/16e3e22d02a05b3670859abdf1a9c7736a7b270b.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/4b2d0a49a8a9ee972b02390416efa3cb03cbf48a.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/8/8c0ed1122a306c6cd839a1f2e2933eba47208527.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/c/c76d68482d1655fac9c03eb8891877d9f1f1523e.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/f/f00c124851c7e9fe0014844d33dd01548f82200e.png"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":"ToForm,\u0022 \u0022IsFilteredServerside,\u0022 \u0022IsTree,\u0022 \u0022ListDataStructure,\u0022 \u0022ListDisplayMember,\u0022 and \u0022ListMethod.\u0022 The entry for \u0022ListDataStructure\u0022 is highlighted in red, with a value of \u0022LookupBusinessPartner_Name_Get Id.\u0022 Other values include \u0022FirstNameAndName\u0022 for \u0022ListDisplayMember\u0022 and \u0022Id\u0022 for both \u0022ListValueMember\u0022 and \u0022ValueColumn.\u0022 The configuration appears to assist in managing data retrieval settings for a business partner lookup feature.\n\n\n  \n   Verify the Data Structure \n Now you can confirm that you are editing the correct Data Structure used in the drop-down menu you want to edit. This Data Structure, for example, has the following Filter Sets defined: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/6/6bb0bbdece043dc2c316430250ca47d8daa634f2.png]\nDescription: The image displays a Model Browser interface for a software application labeled \u0022myapplication.\u0022 The structure is organized under the \u0022Common,\u0022 \u0022Data,\u0022 and \u0022Constants\u0022 categories. Within \u0022Data Structures,\u0022 there is a section titled \u0022Lookups,\u0022 which includes multiple entries such as \u0022LookupAvatarFileBusinessPartner,\u0022 \u0022LookupBusinessPartner,\u0022 and \u0022LookupBusinessPartner_Id.\u0022 Highlighted in red is \u0022LookupBusinessPartner_Name_GetId,\u0022 which contains subcategories such as \u0022Entities,\u0022 \u0022Filter Sets,\u0022 \u0022GetId,\u0022 \u0022UsersOnly,\u0022 and a further sub-item \u0022BusinessPartner_GetUsersWithEmail.\u0022 The overall purpose appears to be for managing and accessing data related to business partners within the application.\n\n\n  \n For instance, the Filter Set named  UsersOnly  is defined to filter out system Users with no email set using the Entity Filter named  GetUsersWithEmail  that we have already shown: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/3/3f5d4f08762604fa3c3745d482e8c9807e7421c2.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface related to a data management application, specifically focused on \u0022Entities\u0022 and \u0022Partner Management.\u0022 The visible structure includes various categories such as \u0022Origam General Interfaces,\u0022 \u0022myapplication,\u0022 and \u0022BusinessPartner\u0022 with subcategories like \u0022Fields\u0022 and \u0022Filters.\u0022 Notably, under \u0022Filters,\u0022 there is an expandable section for \u0022GetUsersWithEmail,\u0022 which has a nested option for \u0022Not Equal.\u0022 This includes two sub-items labeled \u0022Left\u0022 and \u0022Right,\u0022 with \u0022Right\u0022 further specifying \u0022UserEmail.\u0022 The apparent purpose is to outline data query options for retrieving user information based on email criteria.\n\n\n  \n   Filter data in your screens \n Another possible use of filters is in user screens when displaying data, whether for editing or just viewing. From the model perspective, this means using filters in screen sections located within screens or tabs. \n The creation of filters, filter sets, and their usage in data structures is the same as described above. The difference in this use case is that you set up the filter used in a data structure filter set so that it filters the target entity (used in the data structure). \n It may sound complicated, but once you look at the model elements, it should become clearer. \n For example, consider a data structure for a screen where we want to view  Tasks  filtered by their status \u2014 in one tab only those with the status  Done , and in the other tab those with all other statuses (designated as \u201Cnot done\u201D). \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/1/16e3e22d02a05b3670859abdf1a9c7736a7b270b.png]\nDescription: The image displays a hierarchical structure within a software interface, likely for a database or task management system under the section labeled \u0022TaskOverview.\u0022 The hierarchy includes main categories labeled \u0022Entities\u0022 and \u0022Filter Sets.\u0022 Under \u0022Entities,\u0022 there are subcategories for \u0022BusinessPartner,\u0022 which further expands to show \u0022Task\u0022 and \u0022Task Done.\u0022 The \u0022Filter Sets\u0022 section features a category titled \u0022ByStatusAndUsersOnly,\u0022 containing items like \u0022BusinessPartner_GetUsersWithEmailSet,\u0022 \u0022Task_GetByStatus_Done,\u0022 and \u0022Task_GetByStatus_NotDone.\u0022 This layout suggests functionality for managing tasks and filtering user-related data efficiently.\n\n\n  \n The entity  Task  is included in the data structure twice (as  Task  and  TaskDone ), and each time a different filter is applied \u2014 once for tasks that are done ( Task_GetByStatus_Done ) and once for the remaining tasks ( _NotDone ). \n The filter setting in this data structure filter set may look like this: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-01T23:51:33"},"vector":[-0.057698358,-0.037454054,-0.054722663,0.014031847,-0.00737131,-0.0289781,0.0035420973,0.012771983,-0.014923139,0.02303381,-0.007465949,-0.037029363,-0.006714025,0.0011734138,0.033540864,-0.022691943,-0.008318945,0.010353704,0.002994499,0.011358229,-0.013850172,-0.035064846,0.028648663,-0.0023852573,-0.019713184,0.08354077,-2.0121546E-05,-0.02855839,-0.02075749,0.044346284,0.012745646,-0.092836976,0.034034252,-0.045989443,0.009421745,-0.025418831,0.0120768845,-0.016831992,-0.033422783,0.023715964,0.003016718,0.0060407086,-0.01846269,-0.022795707,0.014918847,-0.021780888,0.017709292,-0.004088659,-0.047308475,-0.044395424,-0.0256821,-0.025031962,-0.012861285,-0.027724229,0.058864005,0.035880852,-0.041355256,-0.009936787,-0.05033678,0.026586488,-0.021850036,0.0043202485,0.0047307503,-0.025730249,8.79944E-06,0.030422948,-0.021270374,-0.0002452821,-0.0043496666,-0.006321321,0.020115517,0.037150312,-0.049957063,-0.016975446,-0.04331639,-0.012146568,-0.04394893,0.009616127,-0.06566223,0.029621108,-0.025735114,0.004727994,0.024126235,-0.029545767,-0.012349469,0.01546162,-0.027933296,0.1088679,0.009127734,0.020874076,-0.02561626,-0.03996535,0.05746072,-0.014715053,-0.012624535,-0.0049758484,0.012278893,-0.011677809,-0.015552583,0.010093195,0.027803266,-0.0065832436,-0.032762405,0.008440514,-0.025026796,-0.008665155,0.018343916,-0.048990823,-0.038786944,-0.027181653,0.0124858655,0.03651707,0.021296,-8.682347E-05,0.001